ðŸ«€ Cardiac Ultrasound Segmentation Using Temporal U-Net (ConvLSTM)

This project focuses on automatically segmenting cardiac structures â€” the Left Ventricle (LV), Myocardium (Myo), and Right Ventricle (RV) â€” from 2D echocardiography sequences using the CAMUS dataset.

Traditional U-Net models process ultrasound frames individually, which leads to inconsistent contours between frames and anatomically incorrect outputs. To address this, the method integrates temporal information across the cardiac cycle, improving clinical reliability and overall segmentation stability.

ðŸ”¬ Method Overview

The approach uses a Temporal U-Net architecture enhanced with a ConvLSTM bottleneck, allowing the model to learn both:

Spatial features (shape, boundaries, anatomy)

Temporal features (motion, continuity across frames)

Key Components
âœ” 1. Preprocessing

Reads CAMUS .nii.gz image sequences

Resizes frames to 256Ã—256

Normalizes intensities

Standardizes each sequence to 10 frames

âœ” 2. Temporal U-Net + ConvLSTM

U-Net encoder processes each frame

ConvLSTM bottleneck captures time-dependent cardiac motion

Decoder reconstructs segmentation with skip connections

Output includes 4 classes: Background, LV, Myo, RV

âœ” 3. Training Strategy

Combined Dice + Cross-Entropy loss

5-Fold Cross Validation for reliable evaluation

Data augmentation for robustness

Mixed precision, LR scheduling, and early stopping

âœ” 4. Post-Processing

Anatomical priority assignment (RV > Myo > LV)

Removal of small disconnected components

ðŸŽ¯ Goal of the Method

To produce:

More accurate,

More temporally consistent,

More anatomically plausible

cardiac segmentations than traditional frame-by-frame U-Net models.

This enhances the quality of measurements such as ejection fraction and improves reliability for clinical use.
